Step 1: inspect specialty descriptions for known PCP providers

Run this:

SELECT
    p.PCP_IND,
    s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE,
    COUNT(*) AS CNT
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER p
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
    ON p.PROVIDER_ID = s.PROVIDER_ID
LEFT JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
    ON s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE = l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE
WHERE p.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
  AND s.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
GROUP BY
    p.PCP_IND,
    s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE
ORDER BY CNT DESC;

This will show you which specialty descriptions appear under Y, N, 0, 1, etc.

Step 2: identify the true PCP specialties

Usually PCP specialties are things like:

Family Practice
Family Medicine
Internal Medicine
General Practice
Pediatrics
Geriatrics

Depending on your business definition

So once you review the lookup table, create a PCP list based on specialty description, not PCP_IND.

Example idea:

CASE
    WHEN UPPER(l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC) IN (
        'FAMILY PRACTICE',
        'FAMILY MEDICINE',
        'INTERNAL MEDICINE',
        'GENERAL PRACTICE',
        'PEDIATRICS',
        'GERIATRIC MEDICINE'
    ) THEN 'PCP'
    ELSE 'SPECIALIST'
END
Better approach for your use case

Use this logic:

PCP

Defined by specialty description/type

Specialist

Anything not in PCP specialty list

So your specialist identification becomes based on:

l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC

not on:

p.PCP_IND
Example query to classify by specialty
SELECT
    p.PROVIDER_ID,
    p.PROVIDER_FULL_NAME,
    p.NPI_ID,
    p.PCP_IND,
    s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE,
    CASE
        WHEN UPPER(COALESCE(l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC, '')) IN (
            'FAMILY PRACTICE',
            'FAMILY MEDICINE',
            'INTERNAL MEDICINE',
            'GENERAL PRACTICE',
            'PEDIATRICS',
            'GERIATRIC MEDICINE'
        ) THEN 'PCP'
        ELSE 'SPECIALIST_OR_UNKNOWN'
    END AS PROVIDER_CLASS
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER p
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
    ON p.PROVIDER_ID = s.PROVIDER_ID
LEFT JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
    ON s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE = l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE
WHERE p.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
  AND s.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
LIMIT 200;
Best conclusion

So now the conclusion is:

PCP_IND cannot be trusted as the main flag because the same PCP providers appear under both Y and N.

That means your main identification should come from the specialty lookup table, not from PCP_IND.

What to tell your team

You can say:

I validated the PCP indicator and found it isn’t reliable on its own, because I’m seeing PCP providers under both Y and N values. So I’m shifting the logic to use the provider specialty lookup table as the primary way to distinguish PCP versus specialist.

Next best step

Run this one next:

SELECT DISTINCT
    s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
LEFT JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
    ON s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE = l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE
WHERE s.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
ORDER BY l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC, s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE;

That will help you build the real PCP-vs-specialist list.

